title: Split up iptables(8) options in init script.
message:
Split up iptables(8) options in init script.

Split up the 'w' and 'P' options passed to the iptables binaries
in our init script, otherwise the programs try to interpret 'P'
as a timeout value for 'w'.

Fixes for DataDumpActivity and FireReceiver

title: DataDumpActivity: Restore monospaced font and clean up layout warnings
message:
DataDumpActivity: Restore monospaced font and clean up layout warnings

The monospaced font allows the iptables/ifconfig columns to line up
properly.

title: DataDumpActivity: Use the correct units for setTextSize()
message:
DataDumpActivity: Use the correct units for setTextSize()

getTextSize() returns a value in pixels, but setTextSize(float) expects
a value in scaled pixels.  On some devices this causes both + and -
buttons to enlarge the text.

Use setTextSize(int, float) so that the units are consistent.

Reference:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3687065/textview-settextsize-behaves-abnormally

title: FireReceiver: Do not disable multimode on profile switch
message:
FireReceiver: Do not disable multimode on profile switch

If the first argument to setProfile() is false, multimode will be
disabled.

Compile-tested only.

Reported here:
http://forum.xda-developers.com/showpost.php?p=49951539&postcount=1756

title: libsuperuser: Missing callbacks if shell dies in Interactive mode
message:
libsuperuser: Missing callbacks if shell dies in Interactive mode

If the shell dies while a command is executing, and the watchdog timer
is enabled, the onCommandResult() callback will get invoked so that the
caller can handle the error.  But if the shell dies between commands,
the queued commands will get stuck in limbo and the caller will never
receive a status indication.  This will probably cause the app to freeze
until the user kills it.

The easiest way to reproduce the problem is to try running
libsuperuser_example in interactive mode on the SDK emulator (which has
a trivial "su" implementation that denies root access to all apps).  It
will hang at "Requesting root privilege" forever.

title: Api: Default to builtin ip6tables binary
message:
Api: Default to builtin ip6tables binary

As documented in bug #215, ip6tables from AOSP uses an incorrect exit
status code if the kernel returns EAGAIN, making it impossible to
differentiate between a hard failure and a transient failure.  Users on
v1.2.7 are still running into this because the system ip6tables binary
is still used by default.

So, in the default configuration ("auto" mode), let's switch over to our
builtin ip6tables binary.  Users can still force the use of all system
binaries, or all builtin binaries, through Preferences.

message:

Services to capture NFLOG packets and keep the RootShell alive.

title: First attempt at fixing NFLOG log output
message:
First attempt at fixing NFLOG log output

When using the LOG target, the kernel collects the logs in the background
and dumps them out when we run "dmesg".

But when using the NFLOG target, the "nflog" utility needs to be running
to collect the data in real time.  This isn't currently happening.

This patch starts up a new background shell + service in order to collect
the NFLOG data.  Since the usage of nflog is quite different from dmesg,
Api and LogActivity were modified accordingly.

Note that nflog does NOT currently terminate when AFWall exits.  And only
one instance of nflog can be active at a time.  In a future commit we
should make nflog more sensitive to kills (e.g. terminate when stdin gets
closed).

title: RootShell: Register as a Service after starting the shell
message:
RootShell: Register as a Service after starting the shell

This is an experiment to see if it makes the OS less likely to kill off
the AFWall background process.  Ideally we'd like the process to stick
around forever, both to reduce the overhead of Active Rules and so that
we don't miss NFLOG events.

title: Api: Retry "iptables" commands on exit status 4
message:
Api: Retry "iptables" commands on exit status 4

Various users have reported intermittent problems in which iptables
returns exit status 4 (iptables: Try again).  This can happen if the
Android system is updating the "filter" table (any chain) at the same time
we are.  These updates generally aren't modifying the same chain or rules,
so they shouldn't conflict with each other in any other way.

The problem can be reproduced by applying the AFWall rules while running
this loop in another root shell:

    iptables -N foobar
    while :; do iptables -A foobar -d 1.2.3.4 -j ACCEPT ; \
        iptables -D foobar -d 1.2.3.4 -j ACCEPT ; done

We will retry these transactions up to 10 times.

title: Api: Fix data leak when LAN control is enabled
message:
Api: Fix data leak when LAN control is enabled

The current logic leaves the wifi interface wide open when there is no
IP address assigned.  But it can take a couple of seconds to get a
CONNECTIVITY_CHANGE intent after the IP is assigned.  So it's important
to block traffic until the rules are set up properly.

title: Api: Fix data leak when applying rules
message:
Api: Fix data leak when applying rules

AFWall applies the rule set by flushing all chains and then adding
50-100+ rules one at a time.  This creates a 1-2+ second window of
vulnerability in which blocked apps can access the network.  So
set the default output policy to DROP until the rules have all been
successfully added.

This patch also causes AFWall to fail safe if the rules could not be
applied (e.g. typo in the custom rules), instead of leaving network
access wide open.

title: InterfaceTracker: Remove redundant interface names
message:
InterfaceTracker: Remove redundant interface names

Listing e.g. "wlan0+" and "wlan+" is redundant, because "wlan+" matches
any name starting with "wlan".  There are several of these, and
eliminating them reduces the number of rules that need to be applied.

Also, move the wifi rules up to the front of the "afwall" chain.  It's
a shorter list, and wifi is likely to handle higher data rates.

title: Remove now-unused BackgroundIntentService
message: Remove now-unused BackgroundIntentService

title: InterfaceTracker: Add new applyRulesOnChange() method
message:
InterfaceTracker: Add new applyRulesOnChange() method

Now that we can run root commands from the main thread, the
BackgroundIntentService is no longer needed and the "reapply or don't
reapply?" logic can be much simpler.

title: Implement new fastApply() method to optimize background rule changes
message: Implement new fastApply() method to optimize background rule changes

title: Api: Split static and dynamic firewall rules
message:
Api: Split static and dynamic firewall rules

applyIptablesRulesImpl() can generate hundreds of iptables commands on a
device with many apps installed.  It would be very expensive to reapply
all of these rules every time the network configuration (roaming,
tethering, LAN IPs) changed.  So instead, we will split the "dynamic"
items into a couple of very short chains, and use those chains to
route packets into the longer "UID list" chains.

title: Api: Add new methods to retrieve interface info
message:
Api: Add new methods to retrieve interface info

interfaceInfo() lists the interfaces in /sys/class/net, then optionally
matches each one against the ITFS_* lists to show whether they match
the iptables wildcard rules.  This doesn't execute any shell commands,
but it should probably be run in an AsyncTask due to filesystem I/O.

runIfconfig() runs busybox "ifconfig -a" to list all interfaces, stats,
link statuses, and IP addresses.  This requires a new busybox binary.

title: Api: Add new non-blocking methods to support Rules/Log activities
message:

the entire set of rules

For rules: fetch rules, flush all rules

title: Api: Refactor applyIptablesRulesImpl() and applySavedIptablesRules()
message:
Api: Refactor applyIptablesRulesImpl() and applySavedIptablesRules()

Use a helper function to replace code that was duplicated between
3G/wifi/LAN/VPN.  Simplify the command list and fix error checking when
IPv6 is enabled.  Allow applySavedIptablesRules() to be called in a
non-blocking mode from the UI thread, but retain the blocking mode
for backward compatibility with current callers.

This patch shouldn't actually change any of the packet filtering logic.

title: ukanth/afwall#141: Move interface change handling into BackgroundIntentService
message:
ukanth/afwall#141: Move interface change handling into BackgroundIntentService

Applying new rules directly from ConnectivityChangeReceiver (as was done
for roam change events in the past) may have been a cause of UI
responsiveness problems.  This commit represents the first steps toward
centralizing the apply*IptablesRules operations in
BackgroundIntentService, which will serialize the requests.
